{
  "stem": "10572.6",
  "chunk_idx": 2,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 3.7,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 20,
      "text": "But I wrote my letters to my parents to Crystal Merch in Denmark.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 21,
      "text": "And she would take them out of my English envelope and put them in a Danish envelope and then send them to my parents.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 22,
      "text": "And my parents would correspond the same way.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 23,
      "text": "And this way, we were in contact, even though greatly delayed by two senders and by all kinds of other-- but it helped us.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 24,
      "text": "And then, as I said before, on the-- the-- the end of April, I went to the American Embassy.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 4,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 25,
      "text": "And I passed, and I got my-- the most important stamp I ever saw, the most important paper, my passport with the immigration visa.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "1940.",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "And as I left the embassy, there were newspaper photographers standing there with their cameras aimed at the exit.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And I wasn't surprised at all that they were there to take the picture of the happiest guy in the world.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "I was a little bit disappointed to realize that they didn't wait for me.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "They waited for some know-wells, the American Under Secretary of State, who also happened to be in the embassy that day.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "But even today, I feel that my business was much more serious than some know-wells' business ever could have been.",
      "word_count": 20
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "And then I left England on the 1st of May from Liverpool and got on a ship.",
      "word_count": 17
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "We didn't know the name, but it had anti-aircraft guns on top of the ship because we were going through submarine-infested waters.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 5,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "And the first four days and four nights, we slept and ate and walked with our life belts on in order to-- and the ship that took us across the ocean was the Britannic of the Cunard White Star Line, which we found out later on.",
      "word_count": 46
    }
  ],
